\description{
Performs rolling-window trend analysis on a time series, classifying each
time point as \strong{ascending}, \strong{descending}, \strong{flat}, or \strong{turbulent}.
Turbulence is detected from the volatility of the trend metric itself,
not from the raw series variance.
}
\details{
The analysis proceeds in three stages:

\strong{1. Rolling metric calculation.} A trend metric is computed for each
window position. The available methods are:
\describe{
\item{\code{"slope"} (default)}{Rate of change estimated by one of four
sub-methods:
\itemize{
\item \code{"ols"} --Ordinary Least Squares slope. Efficient but
sensitive to outliers.
\item \code{"robust"} --Theil-Sen estimator (median of all pairwise
slopes). Highly robust to outliers.
\item \code{"spearman"} / \code{"kendall"} --Rank-based correlation scaled
by the ratio of standard deviations to produce a slope-like
metric. Robust to non-linear relationships.
}
}
\item{\code{"ar1_phi1"}}{First-order autoregressive coefficient. Values
near 1 indicate a strong trend; near 0 indicate no trend.}
\item{\code{"growth_factor"}}{Ratio of the last to the first value in each
window (\eqn{V_{end} / V_{start}}). Suitable for multiplicative or
exponential processes.}
}

\strong{2. Initial classification.} Each point is classified based on the
metric value relative to a neutral value (0 for slope, 1 for ar1_phi1
and growth_factor) plus or minus \code{epsilon}:
\itemize{
\item \strong{ascending}: metric > neutral + epsilon
\item \strong{descending}: metric < neutral - epsilon
\item \strong{flat}: metric within the epsilon band
}

\strong{3. Turbulence re-classification.} A combined volatility score is
computed on a rolling sub-window of the metric itself:
\deqn{V_{combined} = CV(metric) + 0.5 \times \frac{Range(metric)}{|mean(metric)|}}
If this score exceeds \code{turbulence_threshold}, the point is re-classified
as \strong{turbulent}. The \code{flat_to_turbulent_factor} introduces hysteresis:
flat segments require a higher volatility score to be reclassified,
preventing minor noise from triggering false turbulence detections.
}
